{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01A6fidsjP4tMdn71MQF1key","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the LEVEL-DEFS and KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1**: The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about how the diff is parsed/scoped — one function's logic for extracting changed lines from a diff. This could be a Unit test if it's about parsing logic.\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it need real network? No — the diff parsing logic can be tested with a synthetic diff string.\n- MOCK-HIDE: If we mock the diff fetching, we can still test the scoping logic.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM dependency here — it's about diff parsing/scoping.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis is fundamentally a Unit test focused on diff parsing and extraction logic. The core behavior is verifying that only changed lines get passed to the review, not the entire file. The failure mode would be if the code accidentally sent the full file content instead of just the diff hunks. I could test this by feeding in a synthetic diff and asserting that only the modified lines are extracted, which doesn't require any external dependencies or integration points. lines from a diff) is a deterministic parsing/transformation that can be tested in isolation.\n\nFor inline comments attached to correct positions in the diff view, the position mapping logic itself is deterministic and Unit-testable, but verifying that GitHub actually renders them correctly might require hitting the real API. The core concern is whether the diff position format gets calculated right and passed to GitHub correctly—mocking the GitHub API lets me verify the position mapping without needing real infrastructure.\n\nThe tricky part is distinguishing between two failure modes: either the position values being sent are wrong (Integration-level), or they're correct but GitHub's UI doesn't render them where expected (System-level). Since the position calculation is deterministic, I can test that in isolation, but confirming it works end-to-end with GitHub's diff view probably needs a real PR.\n\nFor Behavior 3, the core question is whether the LLM can actually spot a real bug in code — that's inherently dependent on the model's capabilities, so a stub won't help here.\n\nFor Behavior 4, I'm looking at whether the summary findings stay in sync with the inline comments posted to the PR — this is a consistency check across module boundaries. the orchestration between generating findings, posting inline comments, and posting the summary. I can test this at the Integration level using a stub LLM with known outputs to verify that every finding appears in both the inline comments and summary. For the full end-to-end sequence on a real pull request, that requires actual GitHub infrastructure and the real LLM, so it's a higher-level test. So I'm categorizing each behavior by test level: the first one about scoping to changed lines is a unit test since it's just deterministic parsing logic with synthetic inputs. The second about inline comment positioning is integration-level because it requires the diff parser and position calculator to work together, and I can verify it with a synthetic diff and stubbed GitHub API. The third about identifying real defects is agentic since it depends on actual LLM output quality.\n\nThe fourth behavior—ensuring the summary matches the inline comments—is integration-level because I can verify the orchestration logic with a fixed LLM stub. And the fifth is a full workflow test that requires the complete pipeline running against a real pull request on GitHub.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence levels to each classification, starting with the scoping behavior at 0.65 for unit since it's pure deterministic logic.\n\nFor position calculation, I'm leaning toward integration at 0.55 since it might involve GitHub's rendering specifics, though there's a 0.20 chance it's just unit-level math.\n\nDefect identification is almost certainly agentic at 0.85—the LLM needs to actually reason about the code.\n\nSummary consistency checking is integration-heavy at 0.55, but there's meaningful agentic probability at 0.25 since the LLM's output format affects whether the matching works.\n\nThe full sequence is clearly workflow-dominant at 0.80, with some system-level concerns around 0.10.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9901,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9901},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c42dede2-f44e-4f88-a23e-62269a884381","uuid":"d5393d04-2384-4ed0-9fb3-e8222d3b618d"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01A6fidsjP4tMdn71MQF1key","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01M5RuhRV9tKGiPyRv2bJvim","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is a diff-parsing or scoping function passing full file content instead of changed hunks — a single function's output, not a multi-module handoff. REAL-INFRA: A synthetic diff string is sufficient; no real HTTP or OS needed. LLM-DEP: No model output affects this check. MOCK-HIDE: The scoping logic is deterministic; mocking the upstream diff source still lets you verify the filtering correctly. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered but rejected because the failure is self-contained inside the diff-extraction logic, not at a module boundary where two modules hand off transformed data.","test_description":"Feed a synthetic unified-diff string (containing both context lines and changed lines for several files) into the diff-scoping function. Assert that the returned review payload contains only the lines marked with `+` or `-` in the diff, with zero lines from unchanged context or file sections that had no changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.65,"Integration":0.27,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears at the boundary between the diff-position calculator and the comment-posting module — correct position numbers must flow from one to the other and be accepted by the API stub. Testing just the calculation function (Unit) would miss bugs in how positions are passed to the API call. REAL-INFRA: A stub/fake GitHub API endpoint is sufficient to verify the position values sent in the request body; real GitHub rendering is not required to catch wrong position calculations. LLM-DEP: Position mapping is deterministic given a known diff. REJECTION-GATE: System was considered for GitHub rendering correctness, but the core failure (wrong diff position integer) surfaces without real HTTP — a stub that captures request payloads is enough.","test_description":"Wire the diff-position calculator and the GitHub comment-posting module together against a stub GitHub API. Provide a known synthetic diff and a set of findings at specified lines. Capture the HTTP requests sent to the stub. Assert that each request body's `position` field matches the expected diff-hunk offset for the target line, computed from the known diff.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The agent identifies at least one real defect in a pull request that contains a known introduced bug.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Correctness depends directly on whether a real LLM classifies the diff content as containing a defect. A stub that always returns 'bug found' would trivially pass while hiding real model failures; a stub that always returns nothing would always fail. Running 100 times with a real model may yield different results, which is exactly the non-determinism that requires Agentic. MOCK-HIDE: Any deterministic mock of the LLM makes this test vacuous — it tests the plumbing, not the detection quality. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow was considered, but the behavior describes a single-model classification step over a diff, not a multi-step agentic pipeline; the minimum failure boundary is one real model call.","test_description":"Prepare a pull request diff that contains a deliberately introduced bug (e.g., an off-by-one error or missing null check) as a known ground-truth fixture. Run the agent's analysis step against this diff using the real LLM. Assert that the returned findings contain at least one entry whose location or description corresponds to the introduced bug's line or code pattern.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.09}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Every finding listed in the top-level summary corresponds to an inline comment that was also posted — no findings appear in the summary without a matching inline comment.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears at the orchestration boundary where the inline-comment posting step and the summary generation step share the same finding list — one step may drop or add items the other does not. This is a multi-module interaction, not a single function's logic. REAL-INFRA: No real HTTP needed; a fake GitHub API stub that records posted comments is sufficient to observe both outputs. LLM-DEP: The consistency invariant is deterministic given a fixed list of findings; a stub LLM returning a known findings list lets the test verify the orchestration logic without model non-determinism. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic was considered because LLM output format could affect matching, but the consistency check (same findings appear in both outputs) is structural and can be fully exercised with a deterministic stub returning edge-case-format findings.","test_description":"Using a stub LLM that returns a fixed list of findings (including edge cases like findings with identical file/line pairs), run the full orchestration layer (inline comment posting + summary generation) against a stub GitHub API that records all posted requests. After execution, collect the set of finding identifiers from posted inline comments and from the summary comment body. Assert the two sets are equal — every finding in the summary has a matching inline comment, and no inline comment is missing from the summary.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — reading the diff, posting inline comments, posting the summary comment — completes correctly for a real pull request without manual intervention.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly names three sequential agentic steps (read diff, post inline comments, post summary) that must all succeed in order. Each step's output feeds the next. REAL-INFRA: 'A real pull request' means real GitHub API calls — real HTTP authentication, real diff format from the API, real comment-posting endpoints. In-process stubs cannot reproduce failures that stem from real API response shapes, rate limits, or authentication edge cases. LLM-DEP: The agent uses a real LLM for analysis between the diff-read and comment-post steps, making at least one step non-deterministic. REJECTION-GATE: System was considered since real HTTP is required, but the explicit multi-step agentic pipeline (with LLM in the middle) exceeds System scope and reaches Workflow.","test_description":"Create or designate a real test pull request on a GitHub repository (or a test-scoped repo) that contains at least one changed file. Invoke the automation end-to-end with no human steps. After completion, use the real GitHub API to fetch the PR's review comments and issue comments. Assert: (a) at least one inline review comment exists, (b) exactly one top-level summary comment exists, and (c) every finding referenced in the summary has a corresponding inline comment on the PR.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.8}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence"